   - If the stack is empty, it means there is no matching opening parenthesis, so return "NO".
   - If the stack is not empty, pop the top element from the stack (which should be an opening parenthesis).
5. After iterating through all characters, check if the stack is empty:
   - If the stack is empty, it means all opening parentheses had matching closing parentheses, so return "YES".
   - If the stack is not empty, it means there are unmatched opening parentheses, so return "NO".

Here is the complete R function implementing the above logic:

```r
check_parentheses_balance <- function(expression) {
  # Initialize an empty stack
  stack <- character(0)

  # Iterate through each character in the expression
  for (char in strsplit(expression, NULL)[[1]]) {
    if (char == "(") {
      # Push opening parenthesis onto the stack
      stack <- c(stack, char)
    } else if (char == ")") {
      # Check if stack is empty
      if (length(stack) == 0) {
        return("NO")
      } else {
        # Pop the top element from the stack
        stack <- stack[-length(stack)]
      }
    }
  }

  # Check if stack is empty
  if (length(stack) == 0) {
    return("YES")
  } else {
    return("NO")
  }
}

